p\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAkt activation enhances protein synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E by promoting the mammalian target of rapamycin (mTOR) signaling pathway, which is crucial for muscle growth and repair. Akt, also known as protein kinase B, is a key player in cellular signaling pathways that regulate growth, proliferation, and survival.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnabolic signals\u003C/strong\u003E, such as insulin and growth factors, typically increase Akt activation, leading to enhanced cellular growth and survival. This is contrary to the option suggesting that anabolic signals reduce Akt activation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAkt activation\u003C/strong\u003E does not lead to increased apoptosis; rather, it promotes cell survival by inhibiting apoptotic pathways.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAkt activation\u003C/strong\u003E increases glucose uptake by promoting the translocation of glucose transporters to the cell membrane, which is essential for energy production and cellular metabolism.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Akt activation enhances protein synthesis by promoting mTOR signaling.","Anabolic signals typically increase Akt activation, leading to enhanced cellular growth and survival."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Longo, U. G., \u0026 Denaro, V. (Eds.). (2023). Textbook of musculoskeletal disorders. Springer Nature","Hughes, S. H. (2022). The Musculoskeletal System: The Musculoskeletal System-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Frontera WR, Ochala J. Skeletal muscle: a brief review of structure and function. Calcif Tissue Int. 2015 Mar;96(3):183-95. doi: 10.1007/s00223-014-9915-y. Epub 2014 Oct 8. PMID: 25294644","Morrison BM. Neuromuscular Diseases. Semin Neurol. 2016 Oct;36(5):409-418. doi: 10.1055/s-0036-1586263. Epub 2016 Sep 23. PMID: 27704495"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60024"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18418"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60024","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60024"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-25T06:08:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-25T06:08:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11136"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74533"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4929"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6d","name":"Endocrine","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23